<webwork-reps version="2" webwork2_major_version="2" webwork2_minor_version="20" xml:id="extracted-section-solving-rational-equations-10-11-4" assembly-id="section-solving-rational-equations-10-11-4">
  <static seed="1604" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalEquations/solveRationalEquations28.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{3}{r+1}-\frac{1}{r-4}}={-\frac{1}{r^{2}-3r-4}}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{6\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{3}{r+1}-\frac{1}{r-4}} \amp = {-\frac{1}{r^{2}-3r-4}} \\
  {\frac{3}{r+1}-\frac{1}{r-4}} \amp = {-\frac{1}{\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)}} \\
  {\frac{3}{r+1}\mathopen{}\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)-\frac{1}{r-4}\mathopen{}\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)} \amp = {-\frac{1}{\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)} \\
  {3\mathopen{}\left(r-4\right)-\left(r+1\right)} \amp = {-1} \\
  {3r-12-r-1} \amp = {-1} \\
  {2r-13} \amp = {-1} \\
  {2r} \amp = 12 \\
  \frac{2 r}{2} \amp = \frac{12}{2} \\
  r \amp = 6
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. In the original equation, both denominators cannot be <m>0</m>. We set them to <m>0</m>, so we can find out what values to exclude from the solution set.</p>
<p>For this example, it<rsq/>s easy to see we must exclude <m>-1</m> and <m>4</m> from the solution set. These values are not in the solution set we got, so the final solution is <m>r=6</m>.</p>
</solution>
